A lot got lost along 4th in &#039;54.Â  Heck,&lt;i&gt; 4th&lt;/i&gt; was lost in &#039;54, dropped two stories below.Â  Better for Oliver.Â  Left up there with greater splendid isolation.Â  By &#039;57 there were even fewer cars on the Hill as homes and apartments (The Melrose, et al) were demo&#039;d for the Court House and Hall of Administration...by &#039;61 the wholesale leveling began and continued for some years...&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
...and life wasn&#039;t always easy.Â  The sixties wore on and while the nights must have become much, much quieter, the days were full of smoke-belching bulldozers regrading streets, and neighboring structures falling to the sickening sound of splintering wood and collapsing brick.Â  Soon Hope Street was cut off to the South.Â  Now not only blocks from downtown, but cut off from any sign of civilization, the mailman routinely got lost en route to 353 S. Hope.Â  Eventually even the &lt;a href=&quot;/CRA_relocation_offices&quot; title=&quot;cra&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;CRA offices&lt;/a&gt; at 238 S. Grand crumpled, the &lt;a href=&quot;/castle&quot; title=&quot;castle&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Castle&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=&quot;/salt_box&quot;&gt;Salt Box&lt;/a&gt; were hauled off, and precious little was left beside the &lt;a href=&quot;/HotelBelmont&quot; title=&quot;belmont&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Belmont&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;/hoteltrenton&quot; title=&quot;trenty&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Trenton&lt;/a&gt; and half-demolished &lt;a href=&quot;/taxonomy_menu/6/133&quot; title=&quot;theNorthern&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Northern&lt;/a&gt;.Â  But that was June of &#039;69.Â  Let&#039;s jump back a bit.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Oliver had signed an owner-participant agreement with the CRA in 1959; the CRA&#039;s own laws stipulated he didn&#039;t have to sell to them, but could redevelop the property in accordance with the Project&#039;s master plan.Â Â Â  His lot was 7,940sf -- about 12% of the four-acre block, but he had the ability to acquire another 23,000sf (the apartment block next door), which would allow him to build a 150-unit apartment house.Â  That would be within the Redevelopment Agency&#039;s Master Plan, after all.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
But there&#039;s where it gets sticky:Â  through the early 60s the CRA began to &#034;redevelop&#034; their redevelopment plan, and looked to renege on Oliver&#039;s agreement.Â  The potential development numbers the CRA had placed on the project in 1962 had ballooned from $300 million to, in 1969, more than $700 million.Â  In short, the CRA didn&#039;t want Oliver and his penny-ante stuff, or, as a friend of Oliver&#039;s said about Oliver&#039;s attempt to redevelop his hilltop parcel:Â  &#034;The hill just grew up around us.&#034;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Oliver came back with a concept for the entire block--a thirteen story, 400-unit hillside structure with a large garage at the base of the hill.Â  Then seventeen floors with 500 units.Â  The CRA and the Feds still couldn&#039;t live with it and the attorneys bickered some more.Â  The bigger Oliver offered--despite his having a 100% legally sound agreement--the less the CRA wanted to hear about it.Â  They were going to go &lt;i&gt;really big&lt;/i&gt;.Â  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
So, back to the Summer of &#039;69.Â  Oliver, finally beaten, sells out.Â  The Caltech Petroleum Investment Corp., subsidiary of The Pasadena Institute (a front for Security Pacific National) buys Oliver&#039;s house for an estimated $500,000 ($2,893,144 USD 2009) -- not bad, considering his initial ca. 1952 investment of $90,000 pencils out to $719,451 USD 2009.Â  In 1967 the CRA had valued the entire block (96,000sf) at $1,000,000; therefore 500k for his under 8,000sf is not too shabby.Â  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
There isn&#039;t much else to tell.Â  The most descriptive and telling element of the whole affair comes from the &lt;i&gt;Times&lt;/i&gt; article &#034;Crew Demolishes Last House on Bunker Hill&#034; dated September 24, 1969, where it&#039;s mentioned that the residence &#034;was pushed off the hilltop perch.&#034;Â 
